## How is Magma produced?

### Factors in magma production
- To melt:
	- Increase temperature
	- Decrease pressure
	- Add water
- To crystallize:
	- Cool liquid
	- Increase pressure
	- Remove water




### Melting
- Decompression melting
	- Melting point of rock is lowered when pressure is reduced
	- Occurs when:
		- Above [[Unsorted/The Mantle\|mantle]] hotspots
		- When magma breaches the [[Unsorted/Earth\|Earth]]'s crust
- Addition of water
	- When Hâ‚‚O diffuses into rock, it drastically decreases its melting point
	- Occurs when oceanic plates are subducted into the mantle
		- Surface of oceanic crust is saturated with water
		- The hydrated crust itself doesn't melt, but water escaping into the surrounding mantle's peridotite drastically lowers its melting temperature
			- Causes liquid bubbles of semi-hydrated peridotite to rise to the surface and escape through volcanoes
- Heat-transfer melting
	- Can be provided by friction, and heat from the lower mantle at magma vents
	- **Assimilation:** Rising magma (deep magma from further down the mantle) transfers heat to the wall rock in a volcanic chimney
		- Causes parts of the wall rock to melt and fracture
	- Typically happens around continental rifts [[Unsorted/Plate Tectonics#Types of plate boundaries\|Plate Tectonics#Types of plate boundaries]]



## How magmas evolve

### **Bowen's Reaction Series**
##### AKA Magmatic Differentiation
- The order of mineral formation as mafic magma cools through various temperatures
- ![Pasted image 20220920131522.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
- ![Pasted image 20220920131956.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
- Magma begins with ultramafic composition
	- Mafic minerals crystallize out first, leaving only felsic minerals to crystallize at lower temperatures
- Melting order:
	- Ultramafic > Mafic > Intermediate > Felsic
	- Discontinuous crystallization
		- Olivine
		- Pyroxene
		- Amphibole
			- IE hornblende
		- Biotite mica
	- Continuous
		- Plagioclase feldspar
			- Continuously transitions between calcium-rich and sodium rich
	- Both
		- Potassium feldspar
		- Muscovite mica
		- Quartz

### Partial melting
**Ultramafic -> Mafic -> Intermediate -> Felsic**

- Partial melting of ultramafic rock (peridotite) produces mafic rock residue and felsic magma
	- At [[Unsorted/Plate Tectonics#Divergent - -\|Plate Tectonics#Divergent - -]] plate boundaries
- Partial melting of mafic rock produces intermediate magma, IE andesite
- Partial melting of intermediate magma produces felsic magma (Rhyolite, granite)




### Crystal settling
###### AKA Crystal fractionation
- Causes the earliest-crystallized minerals to form and settle out
	- They grow around the edges of the magma body's edges
- Explains how one or more secondary magmas form from a single parent magma


### Magma mixing
- Sometimes, two chemically distinct magma bodies can merge
	- When the lower one is more buoyant (likely felsic) than a denser (mafic) one above it
	- Once joined, convection will mix the two magmas together

# Magma and the formation of [[Igneous Rocks\|Igneous Rocks]]

- Plutons:
	- Large volumes of magma rising from the mantle
	- (>100km size)
- Stock
	- A smaller mass of magma split from the 
	- (<100km size)
- Protrusion types:
	- (4 letters, dike is vertical, sill is horizontal)
	- Dike
		- A vertical pillar of magma protruding from a stock
	- Sill
		- A horizontal tunnel of magma coming from a stock
		- "Tabular"
		- Formed when magma exploits a weakness in sedimentary rock
- Laccolith
	- A pillar of intrusive igneous rock created when magma pushes up from underneath sedimentary rock
